they do well on the tests.

00:00:36.820 --> 00:00:37.750
And then they forget it.

00:00:37.750 --> 00:00:40.350
Maybe they memorize it again by
the time of the final exam.

00:00:40.350 --> 00:00:41.770
But by the time they are
30 years old, they will

00:00:41.770 --> 00:00:42.750
have forgotten it.

00:00:42.750 --> 00:00:44.500
And that, frankly, is useless.

00:00:44.500 --> 00:00:46.410
Unless your whole goal
is just to pass exams.

00:00:46.410 --> 00:00:47.990
So I want to give
you some intuition.

00:00:47.990 --> 00:00:51.610
And hopefully, you will never
forget this intuition.

00:00:51.610 --> 00:00:54.240
So when you're first learning
calculus there's much more

00:00:54.240 --> 00:00:56.240
to functions than what I'm
going to do in this video.

00:00:56.240 --> 00:01:00.920
But there's kind of 3 types of
interesting points on most of

00:01:00.920 --> 00:01:01.950
the curves we'll talk about.

00:01:01.950 --> 00:01:03.680
So let's say, let
me draw a curve.

00:01:03.680 --> 00:01:06.310
Let's say the curve looks
something like this.

00:01:06.310 --> 00:01:09.650
You know, if this is the
x-axis-- that's too thick--

00:01:09.650 --> 00:01:11.330
that's the y-axis.

00:01:11.330 --> 00:01:14.580
The curve could look
something like this.

00:01:14.580 --> 00:01:15.620
I don't know.

00:01:15.620 --> 00:01:16.215
Let me see.

00:01:16.215 --> 00:01:17.395
It could look like this.

00:01:20.850 --> 00:01:22.840
And so on.

00:01:22.840 --> 00:01:25.440
And if you have a curve like
this-- and you'll see all sorts

00:01:25.440 --> 00:01:27.260
of curves when you do your
calculus, because you have

00:01:27.260 --> 00:01:29.730
multiple degree polynomials, et
cetera-- what are the

00:01:29.730 --> 00:01:30.400
interesting points?

00:01:30.400 --> 00:01:33.590
Well, the interesting
points tend to be when

00:01:33.590 --> 00:01:35.180
the slope is equal to 0.

00:01:35.180 --> 00:01:38.580
So, in this, where does
the slope equal 0?

00:01:38.580 --> 00:01:41.070
What are the interesting
points here?

00:01:41.070 --> 00:01:42.900
Let me make sure I'm
using the right tool.

00:01:42.900 --> 00:01:45.020
Right there the
slope is 0, right?

00:01:45.020 --> 00:01:47.430
Because if you were to take the
tangent right there, it would

00:01:47.430 --> 00:01:49.440
look something like that.

00:01:49.440 --> 00:01:52.940
Right there the slope is 0, as
well, because if you took the

00:01:52.940 --> 00:01:54.820
tangent it would look
something like that.

00:01:54.820 --> 00:01:58.910
And then right there, as
well, the slope is 0.

00:01:58.910 --> 00:02:01.400
And the line, it really
isn't a tangent.

00:02:01.400 --> 00:02:03.560
It crosses the graph.

00:02:03.560 --> 00:02:06.200
But as we could see, the graph
kind of flattens out there.

00:02:06.200 --> 00:02:09.950
So these are the three points
that you tend to deal with in

00:02:09.950 --> 00:02:12.070
your first semester calculus
class when you're graphing

00:02:12.070 --> 00:02:13.340
and looking for extrema.

00:02:13.340 --> 00:02:15.180
And this is called a maximum.

00:02:15.180 --> 00:02:17.045
And in this case,
it's a local maxima.

00:02:17.045 --> 00:02:20.380
If, you know, if this was the
highest point for the entire

00:02:20.380 --> 00:02:22.780
function, it would be
a global maximum.

00:02:22.780 --> 00:02:24.260
This is a local minima.

00:02:24.260 --> 00:02:27.030
And if it was, you know, if it
was the lowest point of the

00:02:27.030 --> 00:02:28.970
entire graph-- which is the way
I drew it-- maybe this graph

00:02:28.970 --> 00:02:30.480
keeps going up like that, and
keeps going up like this.

00:02:30.480 --> 00:02:32.640
So this would be the
global minimum point.

00:02:32.640 --> 00:02:34.680
And then this is called an
inflection point, because it's

00:02:34.680 --> 00:02:37.000
neither a maximum, minimum, but
you kind of see that the

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:38.670
graph kind of inflects.

00:02:38.670 --> 00:02:40.640
So let's study them a little
bit more and see if we can get

00:02:40.640 --> 00:02:45.410
a little intuition on what
happens to the graph, the first

00:02:45.410 --> 00:02:47.590
derivative, and the second
derivative, at each

00:02:47.590 --> 00:02:48.110
of these points.

00:02:48.110 --> 00:02:51.140
Let's start with a maximum
point, because maybe that's--

00:02:51.140 --> 00:02:52.660
well, let's start with a
minimum point, because that's

00:02:52.660 --> 00:02:53.570
what we see the most.

00:02:53.570 --> 00:02:56.360
You know, when we used to study
y equals x squared, or regular

00:02:56.360 --> 00:02:59.280
parabolas, that was the
most common thing we saw.

00:02:59.280 --> 00:03:00.830
And then of course, if we have
a negative of a parabola,

00:03:00.830 --> 00:03:02.345
it becomes like that.

00:03:02.345 --> 00:03:05.820
But anyway, let's study a
minimum point where the

00:03:05.820 --> 00:03:07.930
graph is concave upward.

00:03:07.930 --> 00:03:09.240
Let's say we have a
point like this.

00:03:11.890 --> 00:03:15.210
So that's the graph
of the function.

00:03:15.210 --> 00:03:19.950
I don't know what that
is, that's f of x.

00:03:19.950 --> 00:03:23.400
So what is happening to
the slope as we go from--

00:03:23.400 --> 00:03:25.270
roughly-- from here to there?

00:03:25.270 --> 00:03:28.640
Well, let's try a few points
and see if we can, by drawing

00:03:28.640 --> 00:03:30.960
the tangent lines, we get
intuition for the slope.

00:03:30.960 --> 00:03:34.410
So let's see, if I pick this
point, just randomly, the slope

00:03:34.410 --> 00:03:35.910
looks something like that.

