The slope is less
negative there.

00:03:54.450 --> 00:03:56.810
And if we go to the
minimum point there,

00:03:56.810 --> 00:04:00.000
the slope flattens out.

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:02.800
And so, of course, the
derivative there would be 0.

00:04:02.800 --> 00:04:05.520
And then as we pass that
point, what happens?

00:04:05.520 --> 00:04:09.010
Well, here, the slope is
increasing a little bit more.

00:04:09.010 --> 00:04:10.950
Now the slope is
actually positive.

00:04:10.950 --> 00:04:15.520
So the slope was negative, less
negative, 0, a little positive.

00:04:15.520 --> 00:04:17.325
And then when you go here,
it goes more positive.

00:04:20.220 --> 00:04:23.520
So let's see if we
can graph that.

00:04:23.520 --> 00:04:24.760
Just to get an intuition.

00:04:24.760 --> 00:04:26.910
Obviously I haven't written any
numbers down, so we don't know

00:04:26.910 --> 00:04:30.840
what the exact value
of the slope is.

00:04:30.840 --> 00:04:32.000
So what does the
slope look like?

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:33.320
So here it's really negative.

00:04:33.320 --> 00:04:35.540
So the slope is going to be
something really negative here.

00:04:35.540 --> 00:04:39.330
I'm just picking
a random point.

00:04:39.330 --> 00:04:42.210
And then, at this point right
here, it was less negative.

00:04:42.210 --> 00:04:45.920
So the slope is going
to be less negative.

00:04:45.920 --> 00:04:52.060
And then here, roughly
here, the slope is at 0.

00:04:52.060 --> 00:04:52.290
Right?

00:04:52.290 --> 00:04:53.070
The slope was 0.

00:04:53.070 --> 00:04:55.550
And then the slope gets a
little bit more positive.

00:04:55.550 --> 00:04:58.050
And then over there, it gets
a little bit more positive.

00:04:58.050 --> 00:05:01.590
So the slope, if we were to
actually graph the derivative

00:05:01.590 --> 00:05:04.570
of the function at that point,
it would be an upward sloping.

00:05:04.570 --> 00:05:06.400
And so I'm assuming this is
a second degree polynomial.

