00:06:30.570 --> 00:06:37.240
So, in general, when you study
your extrema points, and say,

00:06:37.240 --> 00:06:41.190
whether it's a minimum or a
maximum, et cetera, et cetera.

00:06:41.190 --> 00:06:46.640
The way that you think about it
is, well, if it's a minimum

00:06:46.640 --> 00:06:50.790
point-- like this-- if it's a
minimum point, what is

00:06:50.790 --> 00:06:52.960
happening to the
slope around it?

00:06:52.960 --> 00:06:56.560
Well, the slope has to be
constantly increasing, right?

00:06:56.560 --> 00:06:57.760
Even though, for example.

00:06:57.760 --> 00:07:00.260
Even though, as we go from
here to here, the value

00:07:00.260 --> 00:07:02.550
of f of x is decreasing.

00:07:02.550 --> 00:07:04.580
The rate at which it's
decreasing is getting less.

00:07:04.580 --> 00:07:06.190
So the slope is
actually increasing.

00:07:06.190 --> 00:07:07.200
It's getting less
and less negative.

00:07:07.200 --> 00:07:08.990
And then it increases
even more.

00:07:08.990 --> 00:07:11.640
So you know you're at a
minimum point when the

00:07:11.640 --> 00:07:13.800
slope is increasing.

00:07:13.800 --> 00:07:16.950
And similarly, you know that
it's concave upwards when the

00:07:16.950 --> 00:07:19.010
second derivative is positive.

00:07:19.010 --> 00:07:21.490
So hopefully that helps you a
little bit, getting the

00:07:21.490 --> 00:07:24.250
intuition of what happens when
you're at a minimum point and

00:07:24.250 --> 00:07:25.380
you're concave upwards.

00:07:25.380 --> 00:07:27.860
Well, what happens when
you have the opposite?

00:07:27.860 --> 00:07:29.990
Well, pretty much everything
becomes the opposite.

00:07:29.990 --> 00:07:32.440
Let's say that this
is your curve.

