00:07:37.450 --> 00:07:40.020
a very high slope.

00:07:40.020 --> 00:07:42.160
Then your slope becomes a
little bit less, then it

00:07:42.160 --> 00:07:45.320
becomes 0, then it becomes a
little bit more negative, then

00:07:45.320 --> 00:07:47.120
it becomes more negative.

00:07:47.120 --> 00:07:49.200
Then it goes more negative.

00:07:49.200 --> 00:07:54.380
The rate of the slope becomes
more and more negative the

00:07:54.380 --> 00:07:56.740
whole time that we're kind of
going through this

00:07:56.740 --> 00:07:58.830
maximum point, or this
concave downward.

00:07:58.830 --> 00:08:01.240
So what will the
slope look like?

00:08:01.240 --> 00:08:04.200
Well, in this example, if I
were to draw the derivative,

00:08:04.200 --> 00:08:07.520
the slope is going to
look something like this.

00:08:07.520 --> 00:08:10.280
Because back here, the slope
is-- actually, a really high

00:08:10.280 --> 00:08:11.940
number is going to be up here.

00:08:11.940 --> 00:08:14.250
And then as we get close-- as
we move further and further,

00:08:14.250 --> 00:08:16.390
increasing values of x--
the slope decreases.

00:08:16.390 --> 00:08:17.980
It becomes 0 right around here.

00:08:17.980 --> 00:08:20.130
And then it just
keeps decreasing.

00:08:20.130 --> 00:08:22.470
And then similarly, if we were
to draw the second derivative,

00:08:22.470 --> 00:08:24.250
what will that look like?

00:08:24.250 --> 00:08:25.710
Well, the second derivative
is just going to be the

